\begin_layout Section
Resource Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resource management in more general terms can be defined in similar terms
 to the four basic functions of persistent data storage: creation, reading,
 updating, and deletion of resources (CRUD
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CRUD"
description "Creation, Reading, Updating, and Deletion"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hell"

\end_inset

, and business logic.
 These activities take on different meanings dependent upon the resource
 upon which they are applied and the perspective with which that resource
 is viewed.
 As applied to schools or, more specifically, colleges or universities,
 resource management has four general perspective aggregates: Facility Managemen
t (FM
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FM"
description "Facility Management"

\end_inset

), Human Resource Management (HRM
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "HRM"
description "Human Resources Management"

\end_inset

), Quality Management (QM
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "QM"
description "Quality Management"

\end_inset

), also known as accreditation, and Scheduling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Creation in terms of material objects and personnel is the initial creation
 of the objects representing the resources in their respective information
 systems as part of the material acquisition and hiring processes.
 Creation in terms of abstract objects is not only, as with their concrete
 counterparts, the creation of representational objects in the respective
 information systems, but also the creation of the documentation dealing
 with these abstract objects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reading can be taken literally in terms of documentation, but in terms of
 other resources it could be seen as the browsing of a telephone book for
 the school, the retrieval of information in a spreadsheet program, the
 direct questioning of personnel.
 As we can see from the example of the telephone book, reading often implies
 that business logic has already been performed to filter the information
 about the resources of personnel and sub-institutional organizational units
 down to their respective names and telephone numbers.
 This could, however, imply more extensive business logic such as quantifiable
 room usage statistics, employee pay, or the grade point average of all
 the students of a particular semester.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with creation updating can have a two fold relationship of changing the
 physical objects and simply updating stored objects representing the physical
 and abstract resources.
 Some examples would be the refurbishment of a room, the further education
 of an employee, or the modification of documentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Deletion carries this double relationship further, but does not necessarily
 explicitly implicate the removal of the real resource.
 For example deletion could mean the simple removal of software, or the
 demolition of a building.
 However removal of objects representing resources from one system does
 not mean the resource itself is gone it could simply mean the resource
 has become irrelevant to the organizational unit responsible for a particular
 information system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first two of these perspectives FM and HRM concern themselves more with
 concrete resources such as buildings and equipment, and personnel respectively.
 As touched upon in the excurse about CRUD QM's resources are more abstract
 in nature: specifically the curriculum of a course of studies and the abstract
 resources which come to exist in order to implement it.
 The two concrete perspectives, FM and HRM, have as a goal the most efficient
 usage of the managed resources as a goal, whereas QM has as a goal the
 assurance of educational quality for students.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scheduling tries to fulfill the goals of these three perspectives.
 Scheduling is a process of managing both concrete and abstract resources
 to ensure the utmost efficiency of room and teacher usage, while strictly
 adhering to the standards put in place by quuality management, and taking
 special consideration of student needs.
 In itself it integrates three broad management processes in order to be
 able to manage its own resources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work focuses primarily on the scheduling aspect of resource management.
 While it may make short references to resource management processes from
 which it recieves its own resources necessary for scheduling, it will not
 go at any lengths into the subordinate processes of FM, HRM, or QM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It examines the important attributes and dependencies of the resources from
 subordinate resource management processes as they concern scheduling.
 It examines the interaction and integration of the systems which manage
 them individually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While this thesis does not concern itself directly with the problems of
 human resources, facility management, university documentation, or any
 other aspect of resource management, it does mention them often either
 directly or tangentially.
 This is unavoidable due to the associative nature of scheduling which binds
 resources of these different aspects to create new resource types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However the crux of this work is the integration of some of the various
 resource management systems which are responsible for the resources used
 in the scheduling process.
 These systems and the workflows which are responsible for the management
