\begin_layout Section
Overview of the Thesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resources dealt with in school scheduling software and Untis scheduling
 software in particular have been handled up until this point by multiple
 systems; even within the same organizational structure for the same resources.
 Each of the systems and administrative processes for resource management
 have their own taxonomy and required information to model the resource
 both within the system and in every day speech.
 Three tasks emerge for the implementation of a system based upon the resources
 which provide the material for chapters two, three and four.
 These have strong dependencies between one another and often reveal themselves
 to be cyclic in their development.
 However in order to maintain some semblance of structure they have been
 encapsulated as much as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter two will define and model resources.
 It will also codify their attributes and dependencies.
 These items have an extremely strong coupling with the systems designed
 to represent them.
 In order to present the results of the thesis in a more understandable
 manner, the resources, attributes and dependencies will be presented as
 they have evinced themselves, based upon the system topology, instead of
 trying to confront the reader with various stages of incremental resource
 models.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter three will examine the currently used resource management systems
 and the workflows responsible for its supply of data.
 The results of this examination not only have an effect in the implementation
 of system in terms of architecture, but also in terms of how resources
 are modeled, what their required attributes are, and what dependencies
 exist.
 Where system limitations in resource handling exist, strategies for compensatin
g for discrepancies and missing resources will be discussed.
 Where resource attributes are unique to specific systems, they will be
 emphasized and their taxonomy and nature will be discussed in the context
 of their usage.
 It will also discuss, where applicable, system specific factors such as
 access control mechanisms, concurrency and workflow distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter four will examine dependencies between the existing resource management
 systems.
 These dependencies, in combination with various workflows for resource
 management, crystallize into the system architecture implemented within
 the framework of this thesis and give clues as to possible future extensions
 and interfaces to other resource management systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly chapter five will provide a summary of the resource management systems
 and processes.
 It will summarize some of the key advantages and deficits of the existing
 systems and workflows and the steps to harness, improve or circumvent them.
\end_layout

